RAG: REALM ▪ Retriever Training: REINFORCE (Policy Gradient)

Algorithm o Retriever must be updated based on whether the documents it picked helped the reader predict correctly o REALM treats retrieval as a policy over documents o Reward = log-likelihood of correct token given retrieved doc ▪R(z)
= log P(y ∣ x, z) ▪For example, o If Doc A retrieved → reader predicts [MASK] with 95% confidence --> R(A) = log(0.95)
o If Doc B retrieved → [MASK] with 70% confidence --> R(B) = log(0.70)
o If Doc C retrieved → [MASK] with 5% confidence --> R(C) = log(0.05)
▪Retriever gets gradient signal: “increase probability of picking A, decrease for C.” o
Because A yielded high reward, retriever embeddings adjust so that queries like x are closer to Doc A. o Over time, retriever learns to consistently fetch the most helpful documents.

Intermediate Fusion: RETRO TULIKA SAHA, IIIT BANGALORE 14 Credit: Improving language models by retrieving from trillions of tokens.
DeepMind 2022 ▪ In kNN-LM, there is an indexed key for each token.
This causes two issues: o Restricts the size of corpus that can be indexed o k-neighbors returns only k tokens ▪ What if we retrieve the entire continuation instead of just one token?
What if we retrieve the entire continuation instead of just one token?
Two advantages: • For same corpus, # of indexed keys reduce by a fraction of |N| = size of each chunk.
• Each search returns k*(|N| + |F|) tokens • How to use the k retrieved chunks?
